JurassicPark

Target IP: 10.10.126.122
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. They are SSH and HTTP.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the two TCP ports returns the result above. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80 to begin with.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to the web application displays the webpage above.


Pressing the online shop! hyperlink from the previous image returns the webpage above.


I tried to perform manual SQL injection, but I had no luck as the page above was returned to me. At the bottom of the webpage, the message Try SqlMap.. I dare you.. was shown. Therefore, I will use sqlmap tool.

Exploitation


Using Burpsuite, I intercepted a request to http://10.10.126.122/item.php?id=3 as shown above. Then I saved this HTTP request to a file called req.txt on my machine.


And bingo! Using the command sqlmap -r req.txt --dump, I successfully ran the tool against the target machine. It looks like the target machine's web application is vulnerable to SQL injection. I used the --dump flag to obtain the database contents.


There is an interesting table with the name items. This table contains the name Dennis. Is this a potential user of the system? Using --dump flag, I also obtained the users table as shown above. This table contains two passwords: D0nt3ATM3 and ih8dinos. Maybe I can spray these two passwords with the username dennis against the SSH application?


And bingo! Gaining a foothold was pretty easy. Using the credentials dennis:ih8dinos, I gained access to the SSH on the target machine at port 22 as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting file with the name test.sh. The current user dennis has privileges over this file. It runs cat to output the flag5.txt located at the home directory of user root.


Running sudo -l shows the command (ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/scp can be executed as the user root. This binary can be used to elevate privileges.


And obtaining a root shell is simple as shown above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine. GG :)

Flags


The flag1.txt is shown above.


I had to use the command find / -name "*flag*" 2>/dev/null to find the second flag. The content of flag2.txt is shown above.


The third flag is located inside the .bash_history file of user dennis. The content of this third flag is shown above. The script test.sh looks interesting. This file is located at the home directory of user dennis.


The flag5.txt is shown above. This flag is readable after obtaining a root shell on the target machine by exploiting the misconfigured scp binary with sudo privileges.
